data.content:
Build succeeds and all 3 tests pass. Here's what changed:

```csharp
// Before (v2 — uses removed overload)        // After (v3 — explicit generic)
Assert.AreEqual(expected, actual);          → Assert.AreEqual<object>(expected, actual);
Assert.AreNotEqual(a, b);                  → Assert.AreNotEqual<object>(a, b);
Assert.AreSame(obj, obj);                  → Assert.AreSame<object>(obj, obj);
```

**Why this happens:** MSTest v3 removed the `Assert.AreEqual(object, object)` overload. The compiler now tries to resolve to `AreEqual(string, string)` (the closest non-generic overload), which fails with CS1503 when your arguments are `object`.

**Fix:** Add `<T>` — use `<object>` when comparing untyped objects, or a more specific type (e.g., `<int>`, `<MyClass>`) when you know the actual type.
